[src:apache-arrow/apache-arrow] Arrow can be used with Apache Parquet, Apache Spark, NumPy, PySpark, pandas and other data processing libraries.
[src:apache-arrow/apache-arrow] The project includes native software libraries written in C, C++, C#, Go, Java, JavaScript, Julia, MATLAB, Python (PyArrow), R, Ruby, and Rust.
[src:apache-arrow/apache-arrow] Arrow allows for zero-copy reads and fast data access and interchange without serialization overhead between these languages and systems.
[src:apache-arrow/apache-arrow] Arrow has been used in diverse domains, including analytics, genomics, and cloud computing.
[src:apache-arrow/apache-arrow] Apache Parquet and Apache ORC are popular examples of on-disk columnar data formats.
[src:apache-arrow/apache-arrow] Arrow is designed as a complement to these formats for processing data in-memory.
[src:apache-arrow/apache-arrow] The hardware resource engineering trade-offs for in-memory processing vary from those associated with on-disk storage.
[src:apache-arrow/apache-arrow] The Arrow and Parquet projects include libraries that allow for reading and writing data between the two formats.
[src:apache-arrow/apache-arrow] Apache Arrow was announced by The Apache Software Foundation on February 17, 2016, with development led by a coalition of developers from other open source data analytics projects.
[src:apache-arrow/apache-arrow] The initial codebase and Java library was seeded by code from Apache Drill.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:apache-arrow/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] In software engineering, **in-memory processing** is a software architecture where a database is kept entirely in random-access memory (RAM) or flash memory so that usual accesses, in particular read or query operations, do not require access to disk storage.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] This may allow faster data operations such as joins, and faster reporting and decision-making in business.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Extremely large datasets may be divided between co-operating systems as in-memory data grids.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] In-memory processing techniques are frequently used by modern smartphones and tablets to improve application performance.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] This can result in speedier app loading times and more enjoyable user experiences.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] With disk-based technology, data is loaded on to the computer's hard disk in the form of multiple tables and multi-dimensional structures that queries are run against.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Disk-based technologies are often relational database management systems (RDBMSes), often based on the structured query language (SQL), such as SQL Server, MySQL, Oracle, and many others.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] RDBMSes are designed for the requirements of transactional processing.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Using a database that supports insertions and updates as well as performing aggregations, joins (typical in BI solutions) are typically very slow.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Another drawback is that SQL is designed to efficiently fetch rows of data, while BI queries usually involve fetching of partial rows of data involving heavy calculations.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] To improve query performance, multidimensional databases or OLAP cubes – also called multidimensional online analytical processing (MOLAP) – may be constructed.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Designing a cube may be an elaborate and lengthy process, and changing the cube's structure to adapt to dynamically changing business needs may be cumbersome.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Cubes are pre-populated with data to answer specific queries, and although they increase performance, they are still not optimal for answering all ad-hoc queries.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Information technology (IT) staff may spend substantial development time on optimizing databases, constructing indexes and aggregates, designing cubes and star schemas, data modeling, and query analysis.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Reading data from the hard disk is much slower (possibly hundreds of times slower) when compared to reading the same data from RAM.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Especially when analyzing large volumes of data, performance is severely degraded.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Though SQL is a very powerful tool, arbitrary complex queries with a disk-based implementation take a relatively long time to execute and often result in bringing down the performance of transactional processing.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] In order to obtain results within an acceptable response time, many data warehouses have been designed to pre-calculate summaries and answer specific queries only.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Optimized aggregation algorithms are needed to increase performance.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] With both in-memory database and data grid, all information is initially loaded into memory RAM or flash memory instead of hard disks.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] With a data grid, processing occurs at three orders of magnitude faster than relational databases with advanced functionality such as ACID which degrade performance in compensation for the additional functionality.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] The arrival of column-centric databases, which store similar information together, allow data to be stored more efficiently and with greater compression ratios.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] This allows huge amounts of data to be stored in the same physical space, reducing the amount of memory needed to perform a query and increasing processing speed.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Many users and software vendors have integrated flash memory into their systems to allow systems to scale to larger data sets more economically.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Users query the data loaded into the system's memory, thereby avoiding slower database access and performance bottlenecks.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] This differs from caching, a very widely used method to speed up query performance, in that caches are subsets of very specific pre-defined organized data.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] With in-memory tools, data available for analysis can be as large as a data mart or small data warehouse which is entirely in memory.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] This can be accessed quickly by multiple concurrent users or applications at a detailed level and offers the potential for enhanced analytics and for scaling and increasing the speed of an application.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Theoretically, the improvement in data access speed is 10,000 to 1,000,000 times compared to the disk.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] It also minimizes the need for performance tuning by IT staff and provides faster service for end users.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Certain developments in computer technology and business needs have tended to increase the relative advantages of in-memory technology.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] A range of in-memory products provides the ability to connect to existing data sources and access to visually rich interactive dashboards.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] This allows business analysts and end-users to create custom reports and queries without much training or expertise.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Easy navigation and ability to modify queries on the fly is of benefit to many users.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Since these dashboards can be populated with fresh data, users have access to real time data and can create reports within minutes.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] In-memory processing may be of particular benefit in call centers and warehouse management.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] With in-memory processing, the source database is queried only once instead of accessing the database every time a query is run, thereby eliminating repetitive processing and reducing the burden on database servers.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] By scheduling to populate the in-memory database overnight, the database servers can be used for operational purposes during peak hours.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] With a large number of users, a large amount of RAM is needed for an in-memory configuration, which in turn affects the hardware costs.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] The investment is more likely to be suitable in situations where speed of query response is a high priority, and where there is significant growth in data volume and increase in demand for reporting facilities; it may still not be cost-effective where information is not subject to rapid change.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Security is another consideration, as in-memory tools expose huge amounts of data to end users.
[src:apache-arrow/in-memory-processing] Makers advise ensuring that only authorized users are given access to the data.
[src:apache-arrow/page] Apache Arrow is a universal columnar format and multi-language toolbox for fast data interchange and in-memory analytics.
[src:apache-arrow/page] The project specifies a language-independent column-oriented memory format for flat and hierarchical data, organized for efficient analytic operations on modern hardware.
[src:apache-arrow/page] The project houses an actively developed collection of libraries in many languages for solving problems related to data transfer and in-memory analytical processing.
[src:apache-arrow/page] Read about the Apache Arrow format and its related specifications and protocols.
[src:apache-arrow/page] Find documentation on building the libraries from source, building the documentation, contributing and code reviews, continuous integration, benchmarking, and the release process.
[src:apache-arrow/page] Browse the documentation and source code for Apache Arrow libraries in C++, C GLib, C#, Go, Java, JavaScript, Julia, MATLAB, Python, R, Ruby, Rust, and Swift.
[src:apache-arrow/page] Explore a collection of Apache Arrow recipes in C++, Java, Python, R, and Rust.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The Xerox Network Systems Courier technology in the early 1980s influenced the first widely adopted standard.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Sun Microsystems published the External Data Representation (XDR) in 1987.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] XDR is an open format, and standardized as STD 67 (RFC 4506) by IETF.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] In the late 1990s, a push to provide an alternative to the standard serialization protocols started: XML, an SGML subset, was used to produce a human-readable text-based encoding.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Such an encoding can be useful for persistent objects that may be read and understood by humans or communicated to other systems regardless of programming language.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] It has the disadvantage of losing the more compact, byte-stream-based encoding, but by this point larger storage and transmission capacities made file size less of a concern than in the early days of computing.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] In the 2000s, XML was often used for asynchronous transfer of structured data between client and server in Ajax web applications.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] XML is an open format and standardized as a W3C recommendation.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] JSON is a lightweight plain-text alternative to XML and is also commonly used for client-server communication in web applications.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] JSON is based on JavaScript syntax but is independent of JavaScript and supported in many other programming languages.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] YAML is a strict superset of JSON and includes additional features such as a data type tags, support for cyclic data structures, indentation-sensitive syntax, and multiple forms of scalar data quoting.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Property lists are used for serialization by NeXTSTEP, GNUstep, macOS, and iOS frameworks.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] *Property list*, or *p-list* for short, doesn't refer to a single serialization format but instead several different variants, some human-readable and one binary.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] For large volume scientific datasets, such as satellite data and output of numerical climate, weather, or ocean models, specific binary serialization standards have been developed, e.g.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Several object-oriented programming languages directly support *object serialization* (or *object archival*), either by syntactic sugar elements or providing a standard interface for doing so.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The languages which do so include Ruby, Smalltalk, Python, PHP, Objective-C, Delphi, Java, and the .NET family of languages.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] There are also libraries available that add serialization support to languages that lack native support for it.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] C and C++ do not provide serialization as any sort of high-level construct, but both languages support writing any of the built-in data types, as well as plain old data structs, as binary data.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] As such, it is usually trivial to write custom serialization functions.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Moreover, compiler-based solutions, such as the ODB ORM system for C++ and the gSOAP toolkit for C and C++, are capable of automatically producing serialization code with few or no modifications to class declarations.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Other popular serialization frameworks are Boost.Serialization from the Boost Framework, the S11n framework, and Cereal.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] MFC framework (Microsoft) also provides serialization methodology as part of its Document-View architecture.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] With the introduction of reflective programming to C++26, serialization has been greatly simplified.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Reflection allows for compile-time serialization of, for instance, JSON into a `struct` with corresponding structure.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] CFML allows data structures to be serialized to WDDX with the `<cfwddx>` tag and to JSON with the SerializeJSON() function.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Delphi provides a built-in mechanism for serialization of components (also called persistent objects), which is fully integrated with its IDE.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The component's contents are saved to a DFM file and reloaded on-the-fly.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Go natively supports unmarshalling/marshalling of JSON and XML data.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] There are also third-party modules that support YAML and Protocol Buffers.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] In Haskell, serialization is supported for types that are members of the Read and Show type classes.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Every type that is a member of the `Read` type class defines a function that will extract the data from the string representation of the dumped data.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The `Show` type class, in turn, contains the `show` function from which a string representation of the object can be generated.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The programmer need not define the functions explicitly—merely declaring a type to be deriving Read or deriving Show, or both, can make the compiler generate the appropriate functions for many cases (but not all: function types, for example, cannot automatically derive Show or Read).
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The auto-generated instance for Show also produces valid source code, so the same Haskell value can be generated by running the code produced by show in, for example, a Haskell interpreter.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] For more efficient serialization, there are haskell libraries that allow high-speed serialization in binary format, e.g. binary.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Java provides automatic serialization which requires that the object be marked by implementing the `java.io.Serializable` interface.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Implementing the interface marks the class as "okay to serialize", and Java then handles serialization internally.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] There are no serialization methods defined on the `Serializable` interface, but a serializable class can optionally define methods with certain special names and signatures that if defined, will be called as part of the serialization/deserialization process.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The language also allows the developer to override the serialization process more thoroughly by implementing another interface, the `Externalizable` interface, which includes two special methods that are used to save and restore the object's state.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Primitives as well as non-transient, non-static referenced objects are encoded into the stream.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Each object that is referenced by the serialized object via a field that is not marked as `transient` must also be serialized; and if any object in the complete graph of non-transient object references is not serializable, then serialization will fail.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The developer can influence this behavior by marking objects as transient, or by redefining the serialization for an object so that some portion of the reference graph is truncated and not serialized.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Java does not use constructor to serialize objects.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] It is possible to serialize Java objects through JDBC and store them into a database.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] While Swing components do implement the Serializable interface, they are not guaranteed to be portable between different versions of the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] As such, a Swing component, or any component which inherits it, may be serialized to a byte stream, but it is not guaranteed that this will be re-constitutable on another machine.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Since ECMAScript 5.1, JavaScript has included the built-in `JSON` object and its methods `JSON.parse()` and `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Although JSON is originally based on a subset of JavaScript, there are boundary cases where JSON is not valid JavaScript.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Specifically, JSON allows the Unicode line terminators U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR to appear unescaped in quoted strings, while ECMAScript 2018 and older does not.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Julia implements serialization through the `serialize()` / `deserialize()` modules, intended to work within the same version of Julia, and/or instance of the same system image.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The `HDF5.jl` package offers a more stable alternative, using a documented format and common library with wrappers for different languages, while the default serialization format is suggested to have been designed rather with maximal performance for network communication in mind.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Generally a Lisp data structure can be serialized with the functions "`read`" and "`print`".
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] A variable foo containing, for example, a list of arrays would be printed by `(print foo)`.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Instead the programmer may write a method on the generic function `print-object`, this will be invoked when the object is printed.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] This is somewhat similar to the method used in Ruby.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Lisp code itself is written in the syntax of the reader, called read syntax.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Most languages use separate and different parsers to deal with code and data, Lisp only uses one.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] A file containing lisp code may be read into memory as a data structure, transformed by another program, then possibly executed or written out, such as in a read–eval–print loop.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Not all readers/writers support cyclic, recursive or shared structures.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] .NET has several serializers designed by Microsoft.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] There are also many serializers by third parties.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] OCaml's standard library provides marshalling through the `Marshal` module and the Pervasives functions `output_value` and `input_value`.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] While OCaml programming is statically type-checked, uses of the `Marshal` module may break type guarantees, as there is no way to check whether an unmarshalled stream represents objects of the expected type.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] In OCaml it is difficult to marshal a function or a data structure which contains a function (e.g. an object which contains a method), because executable code in functions cannot be transmitted across different programs.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] (There is a flag to marshal the code position of a function but it can only be unmarshalled in exactly the same program).
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The standard marshalling functions can preserve sharing and handle cyclic data, which can be configured by a flag.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Several Perl modules available from CPAN provide serialization mechanisms, including `Storable` , `JSON::XS` and `FreezeThaw`.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Storable includes functions to serialize and deserialize Perl data structures to and from files or Perl scalars.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] In addition to serializing directly to files, `Storable` includes the `freeze` function to return a serialized copy of the data packed into a scalar, and `thaw` to deserialize such a scalar.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] This is useful for sending a complex data structure over a network socket or storing it in a database.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] When serializing structures with `Storable`, there are network safe functions that always store their data in a format that is readable on any computer at a small cost of speed.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] These functions are named `nstore`, `nfreeze`, etc.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] There are no "n" functions for deserializing these structures — the regular `thaw` and `retrieve` deserialize structures serialized with the "`n`" functions and their machine-specific equivalents.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] PHP originally implemented serialization through the built-in `serialize()` and `unserialize()` functions.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] PHP can serialize any of its data types except resources (file pointers, sockets, etc.).
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The built-in `unserialize()` function is often dangerous when used on completely untrusted data.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] For objects, there are two "magic methods" that can be implemented within a class — `__sleep()` and `__wakeup()` — that are called from within `serialize()` and `unserialize()`, respectively, that can clean up and restore an object.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] For example, it may be desirable to close a database connection on serialization and restore the connection on deserialization; this functionality would be handled in these two magic methods.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] They also permit the object to pick which properties are serialized.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Since PHP 5.1, there is an object-oriented serialization mechanism for objects, the `Serializable` interface.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Prolog's *term* structure, which is the only data structure of the language, can be serialized out through the built-in predicate `write_term/3` and serialized-in through the built-in predicates `read/1` and `read_term/2`.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The resulting stream is uncompressed text (in some encoding determined by configuration of the target stream), with any free variables in the term represented by placeholder variable names.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The predicate `write_term/3` is standardized in the ISO Specification for Prolog (ISO/IEC 13211-1) on pages 59 ff.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Therefore it is expected that terms serialized-out by one implementation can be serialized-in by another without ambiguity or surprises.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] In practice, implementation-specific extensions (e.g.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] SWI-Prolog's dictionaries) may use non-standard term structures, so interoperability may break in edge cases.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] As examples, see the corresponding manual pages for SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, GNU Prolog.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Whether and how serialized terms received over the network are checked against a specification (after deserialization from the character stream has happened) is left to the implementer.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Prolog's built-in Definite Clause Grammars can be applied at that stage.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] A representation can be read from a file using `dget`.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] More specific, the function `serialize` serializes an R object to a connection, the output being a raw vector coded in hexadecimal format.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The `unserialize` function allows to read an object from a connection or a raw vector.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] REBOL will serialize to file (`save/all`) or to a `string!` (`mold/all`).
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Strings and files can be deserialized using the polymorphic `load` function.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] `RProtoBuf` provides cross-language data serialization in R, using Protocol Buffers.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Ruby includes the standard module `Marshal` with 2 methods `dump` and `load`, akin to the standard Unix utilities `dump` and `restore`.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] These methods serialize to the standard class `String`, that is, they effectively become a sequence of bytes.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Some objects cannot be serialized (doing so would raise a `TypeError` exception): bindings, procedure objects, instances of class IO, singleton objects and interfaces.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] If a class requires custom serialization (for example, it requires certain cleanup actions done on dumping / restoring), it can be done by implementing 2 methods: `_dump` and `_load`.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The instance method `_dump` should return a `String` object containing all the information necessary to reconstitute objects of this class and all referenced objects up to a maximum depth given as an integer parameter (a value of -1 implies that depth checking should be disabled).
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:apache-arrow/serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Such machines exploit data level parallelism, but not concurrency: there are simultaneous (parallel) computations, but each unit performs exactly the same instruction at any given moment (just with different data).
[src:apache-arrow/simd] A simple example is to add many pairs of numbers together, all of the SIMD units are performing an addition, but each one has different pairs of values to add.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] SIMD is especially applicable to common tasks such as adjusting the contrast in a digital image or adjusting the volume of digital audio.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Most modern central processing unit (CPU) designs include SIMD instructions to improve the performance of multimedia use.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] In recent CPUs, SIMD units are tightly coupled with cache hierarchies and prefetch mechanisms, which minimize latency during large block operations.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] For instance, AVX-512-enabled processors can prefetch entire cache lines and apply fused multiply-add operations (FMA) in a single SIMD cycle.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] SIMD has three different subcategories in Flynn's 1972 Taxonomy, one of which is single instruction, multiple threads (SIMT).
[src:apache-arrow/simd] SIMT should not be confused with software threads or hardware threads, both of which are task time-sharing (time-slicing).
[src:apache-arrow/simd] SIMT is true simultaneous parallel hardware-level execution, such as in the ILLIAC IV.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] SIMD should not be confused with Vector processing, characterized by the Cray 1 and clarified in Duncan's taxonomy.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The difference between SIMD and vector processors is primarily the presence of a Cray-style `SET VECTOR LENGTH` instruction.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The first known operational use to date of SIMD within a register was the TX-2, in 1958.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] It was capable of 36-bit operations and two 18-bit or four 9-bit sub-word operations.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The first commercial use of SIMD instructions was in the ILLIAC IV, which was completed in 1972.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Vector supercomputers of the early 1970s such as the CDC Star-100 and the Texas Instruments ASC could operate on a "vector" of data with a single instruction.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Vector processing was especially popularized by Cray in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Vector processing architectures are now considered separate from SIMD computers: Duncan's Taxonomy includes them whereas Flynn's Taxonomy does not, due to Flynn's work (1966, 1972) pre-dating the Cray-1 (1977).
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The complexity of Vector processors however inspired a simpler arrangement known as SIMD within a register.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The first era of modern SIMD computers was characterized by massively parallel processing-style supercomputers such as the Thinking Machines Connection Machine CM-1 and CM-2.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] These computers had many limited-functionality processors that would work in parallel.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] For example, each of 65,536 single-bit processors in a Thinking Machines CM-2 would execute the same instruction at the same time, allowing, for instance, to logically combine 65,536 pairs of bits at a time, using a hypercube-connected network or processor-dedicated RAM to find its operands.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Supercomputing moved away from the SIMD approach when inexpensive scalar multiple instruction, multiple data (MIMD) approaches based on commodity processors such as the Intel i860 XP became more powerful, and interest in SIMD waned.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The current era of SIMD processors grew out of the desktop-computer market rather than the supercomputer market.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] As desktop processors became powerful enough to support real-time gaming and audio/video processing during the 1990s, demand grew for this type of computing power, and microprocessor vendors turned to SIMD to meet the demand.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] This resurgence also coincided with the rise of DirectX and OpenGL shader models, which heavily leveraged SIMD under the hood.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The graphics APIs encouraged programmers to adopt data-parallel programming styles, indirectly accelerating SIMD adoption in desktop software.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Hewlett-Packard introduced Multimedia Acceleration eXtensions (MAX) instructions into PA-RISC 1.1 desktops in 1994 to accelerate MPEG decoding.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Sun Microsystems introduced SIMD integer instructions in its "VIS" instruction set extensions in 1995, in its UltraSPARC I microprocessor.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] MIPS followed suit with their similar MDMX system.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The first widely deployed desktop SIMD was with Intel's MMX extensions to the x86 architecture in 1996.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] This sparked the introduction of the much more powerful AltiVec system in the Motorola PowerPC and IBM's POWER systems.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Intel responded in 1999 by introducing the all-new SSE system.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Since then, there have been several extensions to the SIMD instruction sets for both architectures.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Advanced vector extensions AVX, AVX2 and AVX-512 are developed by Intel.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] AMD supports AVX, AVX2, and AVX-512 in their current products.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] With SIMD, an order of magnitude increase in code size is not uncommon, when compared to equivalent scalar or equivalent vector code, and an order of magnitude *or greater* effectiveness (work done per instruction) is achievable with Vector ISAs.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] ARM's Scalable Vector Extension takes another approach, known in Flynn's Taxonomy more commonly known today as "Predicated" (masked) SIMD.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] This approach is not as compact as vector processing but is still far better than non-predicated SIMD.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Detailed comparative examples are given at Vector processor § Vector instruction example.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Small-scale (64 or 128 bits) SIMD became popular on general-purpose CPUs in the early 1990s and continued through 1997 and later with Motion Video Instructions (MVI) for Alpha.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Intel's AVX-512 SIMD instructions process 512 bits of data at once.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The IBM, Sony, Toshiba co-developed Cell processor's Synergistic Processing Element's (SPE's) instruction set is heavily SIMD based.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] AMD GPUs since the TeraScale (microarchitecture) are SIMD-based, a feature that has remained in the 2020s microartectures RDNA and CDNA, with a layer of single instruction, multiple threads (SIMT) above.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] On the other hand, Nvidia's CUDA architectures use scalar cores with SIMT.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Philips, now NXP, developed several SIMD processors named Xetal.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The Xetal has 320 16-bit processor elements especially designed for vision tasks.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Apple's M1 and M2 chips also incorporate SIMD units deeply integrated with their GPU and Neural Engine, using Apple-designed SIMD pipelines optimized for image filtering, convolution, and matrix multiplication.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] This unified memory architecture helps SIMD instructions operate on shared memory pools more efficiently.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] (The CPU part implements ordinary NEON).
[src:apache-arrow/simd] SIMD instructions are widely used to process 3D graphics, although modern graphics cards with embedded SIMD have largely taken over this task from the CPU.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Some systems also include permute functions that re-pack elements inside vectors, making them especially useful for data processing and compression.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The trend of general-purpose computing on GPUs (GPGPU) may lead to wider use of SIMD in the future.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Recent compilers such as LLVM, GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), and Intel's ICC offer aggressive auto-vectoring options.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Developers can often enable these with flags like `-O3` or `-ftree-vectorize`, which guide the compiler to restructure loops for SIMD compatibility.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Adoption of SIMD systems in personal computer software was at first slow, due to a number of problems.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] One was that many of the early SIMD instruction sets tended to slow overall performance of the system due to the re-use of existing floating point registers.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Other systems, like MMX and 3DNow!, offered support for data types that were not interesting to a wide audience and had expensive context switching instructions to switch between using the FPU and MMX registers.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Compilers also often lacked support, requiring programmers to resort to assembly language coding.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The introduction of 3DNow! by AMD and SSE by Intel confused matters somewhat, but today the system seems to have settled down (after AMD adopted SSE) and newer compilers should result in more SIMD-enabled software.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Intel and AMD now both provide optimized math libraries that use SIMD instructions, and open source alternatives like libSIMD, SIMDx86 and SLEEF have started to appear (see also libm).
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Apple Computer had somewhat more success, even though they entered the SIMD market later than the rest.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] AltiVec offered a rich system and can be programmed using increasingly sophisticated compilers from Motorola, IBM and GNU, therefore assembly language programming is rarely needed.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Additionally, many of the systems that would benefit from SIMD were supplied by Apple itself, for example iTunes and QuickTime.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] However, in 2006, Apple computers moved to Intel x86 processors.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Apple's APIs and development tools (XCode) were modified to support SSE2 and SSE3 as well as AltiVec.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Apple was the dominant purchaser of PowerPC chips from IBM and Freescale Semiconductor.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Even though Apple has stopped using PowerPC processors in their products, further development of AltiVec is continued in several PowerPC and Power ISA designs from Freescale and IBM.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] It is common for publishers of the SIMD instruction sets to make their own C and C++ language extensions with intrinsic functions or special datatypes (with operator overloading) guaranteeing the generation of vector code.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Intel, AltiVec, and ARM NEON provide extensions widely adopted by the compilers targeting their CPUs.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The GNU C Compiler takes the extensions a step further by abstracting them into a universal interface that can be used on any platform by providing a way of defining SIMD datatypes.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The LLVM Clang compiler also implements the feature, with an analogous interface defined in the IR.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Rust's `packed_simd` crate (and the experimental `std::simd`) uses this interface, and so does Swift 2.0+.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] C++ has an experimental interface `std::experimental::simd` that works similarly to the GCC extension.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] For GCC and libstdc++, a wrapper library that builds on top of the GCC extension is available.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The `System.Numerics.Vector` package, available on NuGet, implements SIMD datatypes.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Java also has a new proposed API for SIMD instructions available in OpenJDK 17 in an incubator module.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] It also has a safe fallback mechanism on unsupported CPUs to simple loops.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Instead of providing an SIMD datatype, compilers can also be hinted to auto-vectorize some loops, potentially taking some assertions about the lack of data dependency.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] This is not as flexible as manipulating SIMD variables directly, but is easier to use.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] OpenMP 4.0+ has a `#pragma omp simd` hint.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] This OpenMP interface has replaced a wide set of nonstandard extensions, including Cilk's `#pragma simd`, GCC's `#pragma GCC ivdep`, and many more.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] "SIMD everywhere", a collection of C/C++ headers implementing platform-specific intrinsics for other platforms (e.g.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] SSE intrinsics for ARM NEON), includes the use of platform-specific intrinsics, generic vector interfaces, and vectorization hints.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] It can be used as a "Rosetta Stone" for comparing these different SIMD programming paradigms.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Another approach is SPMD: write a program that looks as if it operates only one element on the time, then have a compiler widen it to match the SIMD vector width.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] This is the approach used by graphics shaders and more recently adopted by CPU-oriented tools such as Intel IPSC.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Consumer software is typically expected to work on a range of CPUs covering multiple generations, which could limit the programmer's ability to use new SIMD instructions to improve the computational performance of a program.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The solution is to include multiple versions of the same code that uses either older or newer SIMD technologies, and pick one that best fits the user's CPU at run-time (dynamic dispatch).
[src:apache-arrow/simd] FMV, manually coded in assembly language, is quite commonly used in a number of performance-critical libraries such as glibc and libjpeg-turbo.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Intel C++ Compiler, GNU Compiler Collection since GCC 6, and Clang since clang 7 allow for a simplified approach, with the compiler taking care of function duplication and selection.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] GCC and clang requires explicit `target_clones` labels in the code to "clone" functions, while ICC does so automatically (under the command-line option `/Qax`).
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The Rust programming language also supports FMV.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The setup is similar to GCC and Clang in that the code defines what instruction sets to compile for, but cloning is manually done via inlining.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] As using FMV requires code modification on GCC and Clang, vendors more commonly use library multi-versioning: this is easier to achieve as only compiler switches need to be changed.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Glibc supports LMV and this functionality is adopted by the Intel-backed Clear Linux project.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] In 2013 John McCutchan announced that he had created a high-performance interface to SIMD instruction sets for the Dart programming language, bringing the benefits of SIMD to web programs for the first time.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Instances of these types are immutable and in optimized code are mapped directly to SIMD registers.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Operations expressed in Dart typically are compiled into a single instruction without any overhead.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] This is similar to C and C++ intrinsics.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Benchmarks for 4×4 matrix multiplication, 3D vertex transformation, and Mandelbrot set visualization show near 400% speedup compared to scalar code written in Dart.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Intel announced at IDF 2013 that they were implementing McCutchan's specification for both V8 and SpiderMonkey.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] However, by 2017, SIMD.js was taken out of the ECMAScript standard queue in favor of pursuing a similar interface in WebAssembly.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Support for SIMD was added to the WebAssembly 2.0 specification, which was finished on 2022 and became official in December 2024.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] LLVM's autovectoring, when compiling C or C++ to WebAssembly, can target WebAssembly SIMD to automatically make use of SIMD, while SIMD intrinsic are also available.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] It has generally proven difficult to find sustainable commercial applications for SIMD-only processors in general-purpose computing.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] One that has had some measure of success is the GAPP, which was developed by Lockheed Martin and taken to the commercial sector by their spin-off Teranex.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] A more ubiquitous application for SIMD is found in video games: nearly every modern video game console since 1998 has incorporated a SIMD processor somewhere in its architecture.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] The PlayStation 2 was unusual in that one of its vector-float units could function as an autonomous digital signal processor (DSP) executing its own instruction stream, or as a coprocessor driven by ordinary CPU instructions.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] 3D graphics applications tend to lend themselves well to SIMD processing as they rely heavily on operations with 4-dimensional vectors.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Microsoft's Direct3D 9.0 now chooses at runtime processor-specific implementations of its own math operations, including the use of SIMD-capable instructions.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] A later processor that used vector processing is the Cell processor used in the PlayStation 3, which was developed by IBM in cooperation with Toshiba and Sony.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] It uses a number of SIMD processors (a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture, each with independent local store and controlled by a general purpose CPU) and is geared towards the huge datasets required by 3D and video processing applications.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] It differs from traditional ISAs by being SIMD from the ground up with no separate scalar registers.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Ziilabs produced an SIMD type processor for use on mobile devices, such as media players and mobile phones.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Larger scale commercial SIMD processors are available from ClearSpeed Technology, Ltd. and Stream Processors, Inc.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] ClearSpeed's CSX600 (2004) has 96 cores each with two double-precision floating point units while the CSX700 (2008) has 192.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Stream Processors is headed by computer architect Bill Dally.
[src:apache-arrow/simd] Their Storm-1 processor (2007) contains 80 SIMD cores controlled by a MIPS CPU.
